Muskogee Athletics announced Tuesday that the varsity football game versus Coweta will be a home contest on Friday, September 18, 2020 at 7 p.m.

There will only be general admission tickets available for the game. Season ticket holders will need to purchase a general admission ticket for the game.

Parents of band, spirit, and football can purchase tickets, limited to two per household, for $7 at the Athletic Department Office located at the High School on Thursday, September 10, 2020.

General Admission tickets will go on sale to the public for the contest on Friday, September 11, 2020 via the Athletic Department website at muskogeeathletics.com/httickets

post_text:
During Tuesday's regularly scheduled Board of Education meeting the Board approved the the general construction contract for the stadium to be built as part of Rougher Village on the high school campus.

In October 2019, voters of Muskogee Public Schools approved a $110 million bond issue that included a new stadium and field house. Earlier this year the district purchased land from Bacone College to make Rougher Village adjacent to the high school campus. This land just west of the current campus property addressed many of the concerns stakeholders had in regards to the proximity and ease of access for our high school students.

We hope you enjoy this architectural rendering video of "Rougher Village." As always you can visit MuskogeePS.org to view live construction cameras of the work at Alice Robertson and Tony Goetz, view bond payments, and more! #TheMuskogeeWay #RougherPride

post_text:
Muskogee Public Schools mourns the passing of former Superintendent Dr. James Christian.

A 1956 graduate of Manual Training High School, Dr. Christian taught at his alma mater beginning in 1962. Upon integration of the schools, Dr. Christian joined the staff at Muskogee High School before moving into administration.

In 1987 he was named Superintendent of Muskogee Public Schools becoming the first black Superintendent in district history. He served in that position until 1991.

Muskogee Public Schools sends its condolences to Dr. Christian's family, friends, former students, and coworkers.

post_text:
Statement from Superintendent Dr. Jarod Mendenhall:

"As I have reflected on the events of this past week, I felt compelled to speak out. Like many of you, I was completely shocked and horrified by the actions that led to the death of George Floyd. My spirit has been troubled since watching the video and seeing this disgraceful event. My thoughts and prayers go out to the Floyd family.

I am dedicated to working harder to end the mistreatment of Black Americans. I don‚Äôt want to pretend to understand the fear, anxiety and the racial profiling that occurs daily, but I am committed to listening and learning. It is time for change across our country and it can start in each of our communities.

You have my commitment to standing up against racism. To ensure that all children in Muskogee Public Schools, regardless of their skin color, deserve to be treated fairly and without prejudice. I feel blessed to serve a diverse school district that provides opportunity for ALL students. Let‚Äôs begin that dialogue now ‚Äì they are counting on us to lead!"
text:
Statement from Superintendent Dr. Jarod Mendenhall:

"As I have reflected on the events of this past week, I felt compelled to speak out. Like many of you, I was completely shocked and horrified by the actions that led to the death of George Floyd. My spirit has been troubled since watching the video and seeing this disgraceful event. My thoughts and prayers go out to the Floyd family.

I am dedicated to working harder to end the mistreatment of Black Americans. I don‚Äôt want to pretend to understand the fear, anxiety and the racial profiling that occurs daily, but I am committed to listening and learning. It is time for change across our country and it can start in each of our communities.

You have my commitment to standing up against racism. To ensure that all children in Muskogee Public Schools, regardless of their skin color, deserve to be treated fairly and without prejudice. I feel blessed to serve a diverse school district that provides opportunity for ALL students. Let‚Äôs begin that dialogue now ‚Äì they are counting on us to lead!"

post_text: Important information for seniors regarding check-out and Cap & Gown pick-up!
shared_text:
Muskogee High School
May 11 at 8:11 PM ¬∑

Due to Covid 19, we are unable to allow students and visitors inside the building in close proximity. Due to inclement weather all of this week, especially Tuesday our scheduled cap and gown pick up day, the company, Herff Jones, has requested that Senior Cap and Gown pick up be rescheduled for next week, Thursday, May 21, from 11 a.m.-1:00 p.m.

This will allow seniors extra time to turn in any technology equipment, textbooks, or fees owed. It will also give seniors another opportunity to order their cap and gown.

For seniors who haven't ordered their cap and gown, students can email customer service directly at highschoolcs@herffjones.com or call toll free 866-238-5336.

post_text:
Students Meals
Beginning Monday, March 23, 2020 Muskogee Public Schools will be providing Meals to those 18 and under (all students) at four different school sites twice per day. The following school sites have been selected:

School Sites:
Muskogee High School - 3200 E. Shawnee Rd.
Cherokee Elementary - 2400 Estelle Ave.
Pershing Elementary - 301 N. 54th St.
Irving Elementary - 1100 N. J St.
Breakfast 7:30 a.m. to 8:30 a.m.
Lunch 11:30 a.m. to 1:00 p.m.

This is Curbside service ‚ÄúGrab and Go‚Äù meals only. We will hand your child their meal while you are still in your car.

Muskogee Public Schools will run buses to additional locations offsite for student meals as well. These meals will also be ‚ÄúGrab and Go‚Äù.

Offsite:
Port City Acres Apartments - 2103 N. 36th St.
Riverside Mobile Home Park - 4400 N. Gibson St.
Whispering Pines Apartments - 2061 Carroll St.
Green Country Village - 1518 South 5th Street
Breakfast buses at 7:30 a.m.
Lunch buses at 11:30 a.m

MUSKOGEEPS.ORG
Muskogee Public Schools - Notice of Board of Education Emergency Meeting

post_text:
The Muskogee Public Schools Board of Education will hold an emergency meeting on Monday, March 16, 2020 at 5 p.m. The meeting will be held at 202 W. Broadway in the Board Room at the Education Service Center.

The meeting will allow the administration to explain the overall district plan for COVID-19. Information will be shared about the cleaning and disinfecting of the school district. The administration will share protocols for short-term and long-term closures, the plan for delivering instruction virtually to students and the preparation for coordinating child nutritional services to students.

The meeting is open to the public and will take place in the boardroom at the Education Service Center. However, one important way to prevent the spread of COVID-19 is through social distancing, to provide an alternative to attending in person the district will live stream the meeting here on Facebook and broadcast via Channel 15 for Suddenlink subscribers.

post_text:
Thursday morning Muskogee Public Schools Campus Police were alerted of a threatening email to a Muskogee High School student from an outside email address.

Campus Police investigated the threat and identified the student who sent the threat. Based on the results of the threat assessment, it was determined that the threat is not credible. The student involved has been disciplined appropriately and a report will be filed to the District Attorney‚Äôs office.

We have zero-tolerance for any threats to school safety, credible or as a hoax. The safety and security of our students and staff is our highest priority, and all possible threats are taken seriously and fully investigated.

post_text: Check out the trip that Indian Education students had the opportunity to take today to Gilcrease Museum! #TheMuskogeeWay #RougherPride
shared_text:
Muskogee High School Indian Education is at Gilcrease Museum.
February 20 at 10:21 PM ¬∑ Tulsa, OK ¬∑

Muskogee Public Schools Indian Education took groups from Rougher Alternative Academy, Muskogee 7th & 8th Grade Academy at Ben Franklin, and Muskogee High School to tour the Gilcrease Museum. The students were able to learn about and see pottery, sculptures, and paintings from Native Artists.
Our students had a great time and the Gilcrease Staff were very complimentary of our students!
As always, special thanks to Mr. Jack Reavis for being our chauffeur!
#rougherpride #native
Lisa Yahola
Taylor Banks
Sammie Gandy
Chris Mabe
